useful to consider how you intend to use the tool. As suggested in the comments, you should take a look first at <a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/json-ld11/" rel="nofollow noreferrer">JSON-LD</a>, i.e. JSON for Linked Data. This is the primary way of connecting JSON and RDF, suitable if you want to publish RDF-compatible data but want to preserve the main JSON structure for some reason. You don\'t need to use Turtle, as most tools should be able to process JSON-LD just fine.</p>\r\n<p>All you need is to add a <code>@context</code> property which describes how the keys and values map to RDF vocabularies. If you have a service that communicates regularly in JSON, there is no need for anything else.</p>\r\n<p>Of course there are other tools, direct mapping or Tarql-like. You can use them if you have a single large dataset and simply want to convert it and then you are done, but I don\'t think it\'s worth incorporating them into your pipeline when <code>@context</code> is all you need (and is sufficient).</p>\r\n<p>Also in RDF you never have to <em>define</em> a vocabulary in order to use it. You may need it for some consumers, you may need it for reasoning, it is generally useful, but you can do it later (kinda like you can publish XML data without linking to a DTD/schema).</p>\r\n
